Most reaction was positive as the Jan. 1, 1999 date for introduction of the euro approached.
By early 1996 a majority of Europeans accepted the idea and France's Prime Minister was strongly supportive.
Design of the euro note was underway.
By 1997 most British commentary was positive although the government's political stance was "eurosceptical".
Bank officials as far away as Zambia saw benefits from reduced costs and enhanced trade.
Technical preparations continued and although most German companies were not yet ready for the change, the Bundesbank predicted in early 1998 that private investors would benefit.
